  "final_answer": "Using the available data, there are \\textbf{14 students} who appear to have high stress despite relatively low hours, where:\n\n- high stress was approximated by \\emph{Low Satisfaction_Level}\n- low hours meant \\emph{Daily_Usage_Hours below the median of 3.2}\n\nA few examples include Student 1 (0.8 hours, slight grade decline), Student 41 (0.8 hours, no grade change), Student 86 (0.5 hours, no grade change), and Student 98 (2.9 hours, no grade change).\n\nWhat might explain this?\n\n- \\textbf{Limited payoff from effort}: the most common grade outcome was \\emph{No Change} (8 of 14), which suggests some students may feel dissatisfied or pressured even without spending many hours.\n- \\textbf{Academic stage}: most were in \\emph{College} (7) or \\emph{School} (6), which may indicate pressure is tied more to coursework expectations than to time spent.\n- \\textbf{Task type}: many were using tools for \\emph{Writing} or \\emph{Research} (4 each), activities that can still feel demanding even with low usage time.\n- \\textbf{Tool fit}: \\emph{Gemini} was the most common tool (6 students), which may hint that dissatisfaction could partly reflect how well the tool matches student needs rather than usage intensity.\n\nOverall, the pattern suggests their stress may be driven less by hours spent and more by \\textbf{weak academic results, unmet expectations, or poor task/tool fit}.",
